00:00:00.512 --> 00:00:01.983
- [Voiceover] What we're
gonna cover in this video

00:00:01.983 --> 00:00:04.329
is the intermediate value theorem.

00:00:04.329 --> 00:00:07.547
Which, despite some of this
mathy language you'll see

00:00:07.547 --> 00:00:09.996
is one of the more intuitive theorems

00:00:09.996 --> 00:00:12.479
possibly the most
intuitive theorem you will

00:00:12.479 --> 00:00:14.598
come across in a lot of your

00:00:14.598 --> 00:00:16.415
mathematical career.

00:00:16.415 --> 00:00:18.541
So first I'll just read it out

00:00:18.541 --> 00:00:19.968
and then I'll interpret it and hopefully

00:00:19.968 --> 00:00:22.546
we'll all appreciate
that it's pretty obvious.

00:00:22.546 --> 00:00:24.449
I'm not going to prove it here.

00:00:24.449 --> 00:00:27.127
But, I think the conceptual
underpinning here is

00:00:27.127 --> 00:00:28.879
it should be straightforward.

00:00:28.879 --> 00:00:32.311
So the theorem tells us
that suppose F is a function

00:00:32.311 --> 00:00:35.715
continuous at every point of the interval

00:00:35.715 --> 00:00:38.697
the closed interval, so
we're including A and B.

00:00:38.697 --> 00:00:41.128
So it's continuous at every
point of the interval A, B.

00:00:41.128 --> 00:00:43.633
Let me just draw a couple of examples

00:00:43.633 --> 00:00:45.531
of what F could look like just

00:00:45.531 --> 00:00:47.601
based on these first lines.

00:00:47.601 --> 00:00:50.588
Suppose F is a function
continuous at every point

00:00:50.588 --> 00:00:52.970
of the interval A, B.

00:00:52.970 --> 00:00:56.283
So let me draw some axes here.

00:00:56.283 --> 00:00:57.950
So that's my Y axis.

00:01:00.014 --> 00:01:01.847
And this is my X axis.

00:01:03.868 --> 00:01:05.850
So, one situation

00:01:05.850 --> 00:01:06.933
if this is A.

00:01:08.542 --> 00:01:10.356
And this is B.

00:01:10.356 --> 00:01:13.201
F is continuous at every
point of the interval

00:01:13.201 --> 00:01:15.102
of the closed interval A and B.

00:01:15.102 --> 00:01:17.302
So that means it's got
to be for sure defined

00:01:17.302 --> 00:01:18.734
at every point.

00:01:18.734 --> 00:01:21.116
As well, as to be continuous you have

00:01:21.116 --> 00:01:22.734
to defined at every point.

00:01:22.734 --> 00:01:26.810
And the limit of the function
that is recorded at that point

00:01:26.810 --> 00:01:30.645
should be equal to the value
of the function of that point.

00:01:30.645 --> 00:01:33.263
And so the function is
definitely going to be defined

00:01:33.263 --> 00:01:34.910
at F of A.

00:01:34.910 --> 00:01:36.281
So it's definitely going to have an F of A

00:01:36.281 --> 00:01:37.375
right over here.

00:01:37.375 --> 00:01:38.964
That's right over here

00:01:38.964 --> 00:01:39.797
is F of A.

00:01:41.125 --> 00:01:42.938
Maybe F of B is higher.

00:01:42.938 --> 00:01:45.838
Although we can look at different cases.

00:01:45.838 --> 00:01:48.171
So that would be our F of B.

00:01:49.480 --> 00:01:52.239
And they tell us it is
a continuous function.

00:01:52.239 --> 00:01:53.849
It is a continuous function.

00:01:53.849 --> 00:01:56.439
So if you're trying to
imagine continuous functions

00:01:56.439 --> 00:01:57.942
one way to think about it is

00:01:57.942 --> 00:01:59.854
if we're continuous over an interval

00:01:59.854 --> 00:02:01.344
we take the value of the function at

00:02:01.344 --> 00:02:02.627
one point of the interval.

00:02:02.627 --> 00:02:04.809
And, if it's continuous
we need to be able to

00:02:04.809 --> 00:02:07.410
get to the other, the
value of the function

00:02:07.410 --> 00:02:09.060
at the other point of the interval

00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:10.986
without picking up our pencil.

00:02:10.986 --> 00:02:13.828
So, I can do all sorts of things

00:02:13.828 --> 00:02:15.727
and it still has to be a function.

00:02:15.727 --> 00:02:18.960
So, I can't do something like that.

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:20.324
But,

00:02:20.324 --> 00:02:22.117
as long as I don't pick up my pencil

00:02:22.117 --> 00:02:23.860
this is a continuous function.

00:02:23.860 --> 00:02:25.028
So, there you go.

00:02:25.028 --> 00:02:27.627
If the somehow the graph

00:02:27.627 --> 00:02:29.612
I had to pick up my pencil.

00:02:29.612 --> 00:02:31.291
If I had to do something like this

00:02:31.291 --> 00:02:33.511
oops, I got to pick up my
pencil do something like that,

00:02:33.511 --> 00:02:35.067
well that's not continuous anymore.

00:02:35.067 --> 00:02:36.896
If I had to do something like this

00:02:36.896 --> 00:02:38.354
and oops, pick up my pencil

00:02:38.354 --> 00:02:39.744
not continuous anymore.

00:02:39.744 --> 00:02:41.525
If I had to do something like

00:02:41.525 --> 00:02:42.540
wooo.

00:02:42.540 --> 00:02:44.826
Whoa, okay, pick up my
pencil, go down here,

00:02:44.826 --> 00:02:46.310
not continuous anymore.

00:02:46.310 --> 00:02:48.609
So, this is what a continuous function

00:02:48.609 --> 00:02:50.497
that a function that is continuous

00:02:50.497 --> 00:02:52.320
over the closed interval A, B looks like.

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:53.621
I can draw some other examples, in fact,

00:02:53.621 --> 00:02:55.014
let me do that.

00:02:55.014 --> 00:02:56.797
So let me draw

00:02:56.797 --> 00:02:57.630
one.

00:02:57.630 --> 00:02:59.733
Maybe where F of B is less than

00:02:59.733 --> 00:03:01.120
F of A.

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:03.246
So it's my Y axis.

00:03:03.246 --> 00:03:04.413
And this is my

00:03:05.650 --> 00:03:06.483
X axis.

00:03:07.461 --> 00:03:09.047
And once again, A and B don't both

00:03:09.047 --> 00:03:10.164
have to be positive,

00:03:10.164 --> 00:03:11.292
they can both be negative.

00:03:11.292 --> 00:03:14.313
One could be, A could be negative.

